<table id="FlexTable_stacks_in_503_page6">

<tr id="FlexTableR1_stacks_in_503_page6"><td><h3>CANCELED - Survey Analytics from Questionnaires and Textual Social Media Analytics Using Geometrical Data Analysis</h3><span style="color:#0000FF;"><em>Friday afternoon, December 8, Classroom 201</em></span></td></tr>


<tr><td><span style="color:#800000;"><em>(This portion of the event has been canceled due to speaker illness.)<br /></em></span><em><br /></em><em>Presenters:<br /></em> -  Mohsen Farid, University Derby, United Kingdom <br /> -  Fionn Murtagh, University of Huddersfield, United Kingdom<br /><br /><em>Description:<br /></em>Geometrical reasoning focuses on creating point clouds for rows and point clouds for columns for contingency tables (two-way cross tabulation).  Projecting clouds onto planes, leads to useful new representations of data.  Correspondence analysis, which is a geometrical analysis reasoning, aims to show the linkages between pairs of qualitative variables within qualitative (i.e. questionnaires) and textual data.  It shows the difference between the given data and what it would be like if independence was assume.  Therefore, the CA analysis shows the deviation from independence.  <br /><br />Pierre Bourdieu (1930 &ndash; 2002), a celebrated French social scientist, in his book, &ldquo;Distinction&rdquo;, translated into English in 1984, used Correspondence Analysis creatively.  Correspondence analysis is a geometrical data analysis approach and it is the basis for this short course.<br /><br />In Bourdieu&rsquo;s view, Correspondence Analysis is a relational procedure that exposes and expresses social reality as opposed to the traditional statistical tools in which he had a vivid view: In La Distinction, 1979, p 103, &ldquo;The particular relations between a dependent variable e.g. political opinion and so-called independent variables such as gender, age and religion, tend to disseminate the complete system of relations that make up the true principle of the force and form specific effects recorded in such and such particular correlation&rdquo;, (in B. Le Roux and H. Ruanet &ndash; Sage Publications)<br /><br />The focus in this course will be on: <br /><ul class="disc"><li>interpretation of results, graphical displays and other outputs, <br /></li><li>practical implementation using the R statistical and visualization environment, and<br /></li><li>providing intuition, and full understanding, relating to the geometry and statistical processing.    <br /></li></ul><br />We use data collected in various questionnaires, starting from work by Bourdieu on cultural taste.   <br /><br />Other questionnaire analysis case studies will be related to transport, cooking and lifestyle, student experience, consumer behavior, and music appreciation.     <br /><br />Next the questionnaire outcomes express both closed, fixed format questions, and, conjointly analyzed, free text responses.  <br /><br />Finally studied will be data sourced from social media micro-blogging, i.e. Twitter.<br /><br /><em>Syllabus</em><br />Tools: The course uses the R programming and visualization language<br />Topics: In accompanying online course materials, there will be a practical introduction to the R language and environment.  This is for participants who have not used R before. <br /><br /><ol class="arabic-numbers"><li>Questionnaire analysis case study: taking the Bourdieu taste data, detailed discussion of output, detailing the R code used. <br /></li><li>Geometric intuition: the methodology used for graphical display, hierarchical clustering, and putting it all together.   <br /></li><li>Carrying out geometric data analysis, including clustering, using R.   Including publication/presentation outputs, storing data for later work, and maintaining the R scripts that are used.   <br /></li><li>Further case studies of questionnaire analysis.<br /></li><li>Questionnaire analysis, using conjoint, or integrally related, analysis of closed questions, and open or free text questions.  </li><li>Coverage of social media data sources, will be especially centered on Twitter. <br /></li></ol><br />All sessions will be associated with practical exercises, using case studies.   <br /><br />The final part of the course will be a short debate and discussion on potential and scope for analytics, and statistical treatment of data, and text mining.  <br /><br /><em>Intended Audience:</em><br />Practitioners and researchers related to any domains that are encompassed in the case studies, and practical exercises. Students who are undertaking, or who are planning to undertake, any and all such work.   <br /><br />Domains of general relevance include: <br /><br /><ul class="disc"><li>Health and medical surveys, </li><li>Marketing, <br /></li><li>Security and forensics,<br /></li><li>Information and data sourcing through web-based questionnaires,<br /></li><li>Lifestyle and wellbeing analytics, <br /></li><li>Legal studies, <br /></li><li>Political studies, <br /></li><li>Language and literature, <br /></li><li>Digital humanities.<br /></li></ul><br />The presentation language of the short course is English.  Case studies will also be in English as well, however issues related to other languages such as Arabic may be addressed.<br /><br /><em>Supplementary Material:</em><br />Course notes and other support material (code, resources, papers) will be available online.</td></tr>

</table>

